4 Brand Manager Problem and Objective

#Problem Statement:
#The Brand Manager for the grocer is interested in finding out which variables impact sales of Minute Maid Orange juice. This brand gets higher margins than the Citrus Hill, the other brand being sold, and he wants to know what he can do to increase profitability. He wants to increase MM sales over CH. Specifically, he is looking to leverage influential variables to increase sales of MM Orange Juice. 

#Objective:
#To address the problem the brand manager is asking about, I will look at which variables impact purchase behavior of MM the most. To do this, I will run logistic regression and look at which variables have a significant influence. I am also interested in variable correlation so I can understand which variables might be redundant to focus on and to add to a logistic regression model.

5 Sales Manager Problem and Objective

#Problem Statement:
#The sales manager is interested in getting a predictive model that most accurately predicts the purchase decision of a customer. Getting an accurate model will inform probability of a customer purchasing MM Orange juice. The sales manager is most interested in accuracy and not specific variable information. 

#Objective
#My objective in addressing the problem statement, is to pick a model with the best predictions. I would like to know who is most likely to purchase MM Orange Juice. Learning this will tell me more about the customer and create customer profiles of who is likely to purchase which will lead to informed business decisions.

6 Correlation and Covariance Analysis

# Brand Manager Question 1 Continued: 
#What predictor variables influence the purchase of MM?
#Running the below covariance analysis allowed me to find correlation among variables. Among highly correlated variables I ran regression to discover which were the most relevant to build my final model with. 


#Brand Manager Question 2 Continued: 
# Are all the variables in the dataset effective or are some more effective than others?
#Based on the correlation analysis I was able to find what variables had high covariance. I then used my model from the logistic regression for variable selection. 

#Sales Manager note:
#I used the insights from this covariance and logistical analysis-es to inform variable selection for the gradient boosted model. The model turned out to be the best model for the sales manager's problem. 


#Remove target Variable
OJ_C <-OJ[-1]

#Data Standardization
scales <- build_scales(OJ_C, verbose = TRUE)
## [1] "build_scales: I will compute scale on  13 numeric columns."
## [1] "build_scales: it took me: 0s to compute scale for 13 numeric columns."
OJ_C <- fast_scale(OJ_C, scales = scales, verbose = TRUE)
## [1] "fast_scale: I will scale 13 numeric columns."
## [1] "fast_scale: it took me: 0s to scale 13 numeric columns."
#Calculate variance-covariance matrix
cov_OJ <-cov(OJ_C)

#EigenValues and EigenVector
e_OJ<-eigen(cov_OJ)

eigenvalues_OJ <- e_OJ$values
eigenvectors_OJ<- e_OJ$vectors
length(eigenvalues_OJ) #counts the number of eigenvalues
## [1] 13
#Variance Estimation
var_explained<- round(eigenvalues_OJ/sum(eigenvalues_OJ),2)

#Cumulative Variance
cumulative_var <- cumsum(var_explained)
cumulative_var
##  [1] 0.32 0.57 0.73 0.83 0.91 0.97 1.00 1.00 1.00 1.00 1.00 1.00 1.00
#Convert Data to Matrix
OJ_Matrix<- as.matrix(OJ_C) 

#Note: The matrix helped me with Variable selection as it showed which variables had high correlation. From the findings, I was able to build a list of variables that were redundant and could possibly be removed from the model.

#Viewing first 5 components to get us to 90% Variance
pca_OJ<- OJ_Matrix %*% eigenvectors_OJ[,-c(6:13)] 

#Testing for Correlation
round(cor(pca_OJ),3)
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,]    1    0    0    0    0
## [2,]    0    1    0    0    0
## [3,]    0    0    1    0    0
## [4,]    0    0    0    1    0
## [5,]    0    0    0    0    1
#Correlation Visualization

OJ_C2 <-OJ[-1]

OJ.pca <- prcomp(OJ_C2, center = TRUE,scale. = TRUE)

#Plotting correlation among values and adding bones to analyze correlation among variables. This helped with variable selection. 

fviz_pca_ind(OJ.pca, pointsize = 1, pointshape = 21, fill = "#310FEF",

7 Exploring Variables and Models

# Brand Manager Question 1: 
#What predictor variables influence the purchase of MM?
#To answer this question I ran a simple regression model to find significant P-Values. According to the model, PriceCH, PriceMM, DiscMM, LoyalCH and PctDiscMM were all significant predictors of MM purchase. In other words they had a P value of less than .05. I also noticed correlation between variables which led me to run a covariance analysis. 

#Brand Manager Question 2: 
# Are all the variables in the dataset effective or are some more effective than others?
# There is varying levels of effectiveness for variables. During variable selection I ran some correlated variables individually to compare effectiveness via P-value. This helped with variable selection in my logistic model to improve predictions. 

#I ran the following models to looking at the predictive strength of the variables. I looked at some specific variables that were highly correlated and to help with feature selection. If two variables were highly correlated I looked at their P-values and coefficient estimates to decide which one to add to my models.

8 GLM Prediction Model

# Brand Manager Question 1 Continued: 
#What predictor variables influence the purchase of MM?
#The additive logistic model 'OJPrediction2' includes the impactful variables that are not closely correlated with each other.

#Brand Manager Question 2 Continued: 
#Are all the variables in the dataset effective or are some more effective than others?
#Addressing collinearity by removing less effective predictive variables helps with the predictive power of the model. It is also helpful for better understanding business opportunities. 


#Sales Manager Question 1:
#Can you build a predictive model that can inform him the probability of customers buying MM?
#The below glm predicts the purchase behavior with less accuracy than the gradient boosted model we will visit in a subsequent section. 


#Splitting the Data
set.seed(1234)
partition <- createDataPartition(OJ$Purchase, p=0.7 , list=FALSE)

OJTrain <- OJ[partition,]
OJTest <- OJ[-partition,]

#Building the model
OJPrediction2 <- glm(Purchase ~ PriceMM+DiscMM+SpecialCH+SpecialMM+LoyalCH+PctDiscCH, data = OJTrain, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
##step_downsample(Purchase,under_ratio = 1.2)

#Class Imbalance: I did not address this with code, the yes variable was only 1.56 times more frequent than no in 'Purchase'. This imbalance was not enough to warrant a change to the model

9 Gradient Boosted Model

#Sales Manager Question 2:
#How good is the model in its predictions?
#The model is good in its predictive power and variable selection allowed it to be even better by improving RMSE and RSQ. To get a most accurate predictor of MM Orange Juice purchases I would recommend using the Gradient boosted model. While the logistic model has good accuracy at over 80%, it has a much higher RMSE at 4.5 while the gradient boosted model has a low RMSE of .32. 

OJ2 <- OJ %>%
  mutate(Purchase = as.numeric(Purchase))

#Split Dataset

set.seed(123)
Split2 <- initial_split(OJ2, prop = 0.8,
strata = Purchase)
train2 <- training(Split2)
test2 <- testing(Split2)

#Model Formulation

####Use prior analysis for feature selection

rec_OJ <- recipe(Purchase ~ PriceMM+DiscMM+SpecialCH+SpecialMM+LoyalCH+PctDiscCH, train2) %>%
prep(training = train2)

#Model
model_OJ <- boost_tree(
trees = tune(),
tree_depth = tune(),
learn_rate = tune()) %>%
set_engine("xgboost", verbosity = 0) %>%
set_mode("regression")

#Tuning: XGBoost helps us tune our model and find the best hyperparameters combination that allows us to get accurate predictions. The hyperparameters are tuned through a grid search or "tune()". 

hyper_grid <- grid_regular(
  trees(),
  tree_depth(),
  learn_rate(),
  levels = 4)

OJ_folds <- vfold_cv(train2, v=5)

#Information Aggregation

OJ_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(model_OJ) %>%
  add_recipe(rec_OJ)

#Compute Performance

set.seed(1234)
OJ_tune <- 
  OJ_wf %>% 
  tune_grid(
    resamples = OJ_folds,
    grid = hyper_grid,
    metrics = metric_set(rmse)
  ) 

#Model Selection: I used the following code to select the best hyperparamater combination. Or the combination that led to the best RMSE. "select_best" was the command that allowed me to figure that out. 

best_model <- OJ_tune %>%
  select_best("rmse")

best_model
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   trees tree_depth learn_rate .config              
##   <int>      <int>      <dbl> <chr>                
## 1   667          1        0.1 Preprocessor1_Model14
#Finalizing Workflow

final_workflow <- 
  OJ_wf %>% 
  finalize_workflow(best_model)

#Fitting the Model

final_fit <- 
  final_workflow %>%
  last_fit(split = Split2) 

final_fit %>%
  collect_metrics()

10 Brand Manager Recommendations and Data Overview

#Recommendations: 
#Discounts offered on Minute made orange juice strongly impact purchase behavior. We see a low p-value and coefficient estimate -2.7 suggesting not offering discounts has a negative impact on sales. CH orange juice also sees an increase in sales when offering discount and is a significant indicator of purchase behavior with a low p-value and high coefficient estimate. This presents an opportunity for a discount sales strategy. The strategy should take into account what would increase the percentage of OJ purchases MM over CH. This might include offering a steeper discount for MM OJ over CH for a temporary period of time. 
#Brand loyalty to CH is also a strong indicator of purchasing with a low P-Value and very high coefficient estimate at 6.4. Suggesting that customers who have previously purchased CH are much more likely to do it again. Offering a enticing discount might help to lure customers who usually buy CH juice. Evidence for this assertion can be seen in the significance of the price variables. Based on p-value, which is lower than .05, MM price is strong indicator of purchasing. Suggesting that CH's brand loyal customers could have been acquired because of their price point. This is further backed up by the significance of the price difference variables. 
#Since the concern is maximizing profits by increasing purchases of MM OJ, which has higher margins, I would not recommend a permanent price discount. Rather, a focus on creating brand loyalty to MM OJ would be advisable. Specials have a lower impact on purchase behavior but may be worth exploring also. Higher Loyalty points for MM OJ could be a good way to influence purchase decisions while having a lower impact on margin.
